      <h2>Virtual EA Support That Operates Like a Senior Hire</h2>
      <p>The "virtual assistant" market is bimodal. On one end: agencies funnelling junior workers through templates. On the other: senior solo operators who could be your in-office EA but choose remote. This is the latter.</p>

      <p>If you've been disappointed by VA experiences in the past, the difference is usually not effort or hours: it's seniority of judgment. A senior virtual EA handles ambiguity. Decides who to escalate to and who to handle directly. Drafts your board update without 14 review cycles. That's the difference.</p>

      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-7);">What I Cover Remotely</h2>
      <ul style="color: var(--ink-muted); padding-left: var(--space-5);">
        <li><strong>Calendar &amp; inbox:</strong> Triage rules, meeting prep, follow-ups, scheduling chess.</li>
        <li><strong>Stakeholder coordination:</strong> Investor updates, board prep, partner liaison, internal comms.</li>
        <li><strong>Operations systems:</strong> CRM cleanup, SLA dashboards, decision logs, weekly cadence.</li>
        <li><strong>Project execution:</strong> Cross-functional initiatives moved end-to-end with status discipline.</li>
        <li><strong>Hiring &amp; onboarding:</strong> Agent and team onboarding playbooks (200+ agents to date).</li>
        <li><strong>Travel &amp; events:</strong> Multi-city itineraries, off-site coordination, conference logistics.</li>
        <li><strong>Executive communication:</strong> LinkedIn, ghostwriting, presentations, board pack assembly.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-7);">Time Zones &amp; Availability</h2>
      <p>Based in Nairobi, Kenya (EAT, UTC+3). Working hours overlap meaningfully with:</p>
      <ul style="color: var(--ink-muted); padding-left: var(--space-5);">
        <li><strong>Europe (CET):</strong> 09:00–17:00 CET = 10:00–18:00 EAT, full overlap.</li>
        <li><strong>US East (EST):</strong> 01:00–11:00 EST overlap with EAT working day. Most US founders find this is an advantage: I run their morning while they're still in bed.</li>
        <li><strong>US West (PST):</strong> Async-first, with shifted check-ins for live calls.</li>
        <li><strong>Africa &amp; Middle East:</strong> Native time zone, full coverage.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-7);">How Engagements Work</h2>
      <p>Three formats, depending on scope:</p>
      <ol style="color: var(--ink-muted); padding-left: var(--space-5);">
        <li><strong>Hourly retainer (10–20 hrs/week):</strong> Best for ongoing EA support: calendar, inbox, prep, follow-up.</li>
        <li><strong>Monthly retainer (full embedded):</strong> Chief-of-staff level: owning initiatives, board prep, decision logs.</li>
        <li><strong>Project-based:</strong> Market entry, system builds, agent onboarding, one-off launches.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>We agree the right format in the discovery call. No three-month minimums. No setup fees.</p>

      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-7);">What Makes This Different</h2>
      <p>Most VA agencies sell hours. I sell hours-back-per-week. The metric I track is the same one you should: how much of your time was returned to high-leverage work this week. <a href="/case-studies/">Past clients</a> consistently report 15+ hours reclaimed weekly.</p>
      <p>For more on operating cadence and methodology, see <a href="/services/">the services page</a> or <a href="/case-studies/">the case studies</a>.</p>
